<paper id="1574837706"><title>Towards a formalization of the Unified Modeling Language</title><year>1997</year><authors><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="355693066">Ruth Breu</author><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="2060029577">Ursula Hinkel</author><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="2173930862">Christoph Hofmann</author><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="2252082860">Cornel Klein</author><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="2282312329">Barbara Paech</author><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="151827428">Bernhard Rumpe</author><author org="Technische Universität München;" id="303639788">Veronika Thurner</author></authors><n_citation>100</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>4274063</reference><reference>1486228385</reference><reference>1511699776</reference><reference>1519331687</reference><reference>1567698670</reference><reference>1583355384</reference><reference>1591124131</reference><reference>1754800484</reference><reference>2099529102</reference><reference>2139907081</reference><reference>2169802556</reference></references><venue id="1177184315" type="C">European Conference on Object-Oriented Programming</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0053386</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.45812">Programming language</keyword><keyword weight="0.71906">UML tool</keyword><keyword weight="0.58396">Unified Modeling Language</keyword><keyword weight="0.43739">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.55649">Object language</keyword><keyword weight="0.5495">Activity diagram</keyword><keyword weight="0.81243">Applications of UML</keyword><keyword weight="0.68263">Object Constraint Language</keyword><keyword weight="0.62857">Systems Modeling Language</keyword><keyword weight="0.64335">Class diagram</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>The Unified Modeling Language UML is a language for specifying, visualizing and documenting object-oriented systems. UML combines the concepts of OOA/OOD, OMT and OOSE and is intended as a standard in the domain of object-oriented analysis and design. Due to the missing formal, mathematical foundation of UML the syntax and the semantics of a number of UML constructs are not precisely defined. This paper outlines a proposal for the formal foundation of UML that is based on a mathematical system model.</abstract></paper>